    <item>
      <title>Men in the Night</title>
      <link>/posts/poem--men-in-the-night/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 22 Dec 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><author>info@sambw.me (Sam Bennett-Williams)</author>
      <guid>/posts/poem--men-in-the-night/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Dark shadows at the window&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;Dark houses are silent.&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;Dogs stop barking.&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;Wind stops blowing.&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;Figures keep coming.&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;Seconds take minutes&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;Minutes take hours&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;Hours take days.&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;Men in the night take people&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;Away… away,&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;To where they’ll never come back.&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;Men in the night keep coming.&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;em&gt;Poem that I wrote many years ago&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Reason for the Blog</title>
      <link>/posts/reason-for-the-blog/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 22 Dec 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><author>info@sambw.me (Sam Bennett-Williams)</author>
      <guid>/posts/reason-for-the-blog/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;I self published my first book, &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1520218400/ref=ox_sc_saved_image_9?smid=ATVPDKIKX0DER&amp;amp;psc=1&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;The Sharpe Chronicles: Alexander&amp;rsquo;s Genesis&lt;/a&gt;&#xD;&#xA;, in December 2016. I really did love the process of writing it, and the reaction of people reading it (those that did!). Since then, I&amp;rsquo;ve tried to work on the sequel, but I&amp;rsquo;ve had so much trouble with inspiration. It also was a completely different process for me the second time around.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;With the first book, it came from a dream and the plot sort of grew naturally and morphed into the book that was published. With the second, I have a clear sense of where I want to go, and an outline that I want to follow. Maybe this is the issue? the way my creative brain works it&amp;rsquo;s much harder to fill in the gaps of the story then to just let it flow naturally.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
